Homework 4¶

Author: Mateusz Sieniawski¶

I was working on house pricing dataset (https://github.com/pbiecek/InterpretableMachineLearning2020/issues/6).

(4)¶

First I trained a XGBoost model. I found two observation such that their CP profiles for variable "longitude" differ.

In [11]:

For the first observation (blue) we that moving to the right makes the price lower, wheras moving to the left makes the price larger.

For the second observation (orange) changing longitude a lot (either to the left or right) makes the price decrease a little bit.

I was wondering why would this happen, so I looked at the map:

In [16]:
Out[16]:

Now everthing makes sense! Moving the first observation (at the top) to the left makes it closer to the city center thus increasing the price. Moving it to the right makes it farther from the most developed part of the city thus making the price decrease.

The second observation (at the bottom) is already very far away from the city center, thus moving it right or left does not change the price that much. This house is next to a high-speed road, which explains the small decrease in price if it was moved in either left or right direction (now the house is priced about USD$50k higher because of a nearby high-speed road)

(5)¶

The second model I trained was LightGBM. Generally profiles of these two (XGBoost and LightGBM) looked very similar. In particular the profiles for the two most important features ('longitude' and 'grade') looked almost the same for most observations. After a long search I found an observation, that it's CP profiles differ:

In [34]:
 

XGBoost CP profile:

LightGBM CP profile:

Both models have tendency to lower the price if the building was built between 1950 and 2000:

In [36]:
 

XGBoost:
In [38]:
 

LightGBM:

It actually makes sense. The new buildings (built after 2000) might have their price higher due to the "freshness" of the building. A new building is more attractive to the consumer. It really makes a difference if a building is 5 or 10 years old. But it doesn't makes much difference if a building is 40 or 45 years old.

On the other hand, the old building might also have higher prices as many people value "antique" building and are wiling to pay much to live in them.

Another explanation would be that if buildings built between 1950 and 2000 were in an estate which location is not as attractive. For example the older buildings might have been mostly located in a city center, thus they are more valuable. I averaged the longitudes and latiduted of 1) building built between 1950 and 2000 2) building built before 1950 or after 2000 and pinned them on the map. Actually, my hypothesis was true

In summary, I don't know why LightGBM penalized this observation so much for beeing built in 1967. Or rather, why XGBoost didn't penalized it, as both models generally tend to do it.

I even looked at the trees produced by both models (files xgb.png and lgb.png for XGBoost and LightGBM respectively) to find anything suspicious, but unfortuneatly I was unable to do so. The plots have huge sizes therefore I don't show them here as there would be nothing visible.

Bonus¶

I also did an experiment. I added an additional feature into the data, which was pure noise (sampled from a normal distribution). I was wondering if the model (XGBoost) would use it in its predictions. The result was that indeed the noise had an impact on predictions. It could even change the prediction by as much as USD$30k!
